Answer to the seventh article which begins: “ Also because that the mariners are constrained so that they are not able to 5511 their herrings in that part, etc.’'

The mariners are at their own will as is premised above and at all times have used to go with their herrings into their own parts where the wind serves them. Without that the said mariners are constrained as is above said, as the people of Yarmouth will be able to prove in this present parlia- ment.

Answer to the eighth article which begins: “ Also when the herrings pass into private hands, etc.'’

Herring is not sold by constraint, for the fair of Yarmouth is free as abovesaid, and if any private person should have misdone to the prejudice of the said fair he may be punished for his trespass as is abovesaid.
